        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer654609404" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1959709461721325862">&quot;Long Day&apos;s Journey Into Night&quot; meets &quot;The Time Of Your Life&quot; with dire consequences. Like many of O&apos;Neill&apos;s later works it is long, often dismal and alcohol-infused but filled with memorable characters. In this particular play, most of them are archetypes. There is a fair amount of dark comedy as well. It would be a grand experience for a team of talented actors. I&apos;m not sure the same would hold true for the typical contemporary audience.<br/><br/>I appreciated it more now than when I first read it over </span>
  <span id="freeText1959709461721325862" style="display:none">"Long Day's Journey Into Night" meets "The Time Of Your Life" with dire consequences. Like many of O'Neill's later works it is long, often dismal and alcohol-infused but filled with memorable characters. In this particular play, most of them are archetypes. There is a fair amount of dark comedy as well. It would be a grand experience for a team of talented actors. I'm not sure the same would hold true for the typical contemporary audience.<br /><br />I appreciated it more now than when I first read it over thirty years ago. The only lingering complaint is that O'Neill overuses the phrase/concept of "pipe dreams". By Act Three one begins to wonder if it still refers to the delusional fantasies one believes in while puffing away on tobacco. By Act Four it simply feels like the author has put down his metaphorical smoking pipe, exchanging it for the lead pipe of overemphasis he feels he needs to drive his point home.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1959709461721325862" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


